  <sect1 id="intro">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <para>
      The Swap Management utility helps you control the size and settings of
      your swap partition(s) and files.
    </para>
    <sect2 id="whats-swap">
      <title>What is Swap?</title>
      <para>
	Swap is an extension of memory.  Your system has RAM in it.
	There are times that the RAM alone is not enough and the RAM fills up.  The
	computer then uses your swap space alongside your memory.
      </para>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>
  
  <sect1 id="interface">
    <title>Interface Overview</title>
    <para>
      <figure id="main-interface">
	<title>Swap Management Interface</title>
	<screenshot>
	  <screeninfo>Main Window</screeninfo>
	  <graphic fileref="fig/main_layout.png" srccredit="Kevin Breit"></graphic>
	</screenshot>
      </figure>
    </para>

    <para>
      <inlinegraphic fileref="fig/full-1.png"></inlinegraphic>
      <guilabel>Partition Overview</guilabel>
      This is where your total memory information is shown.  It displays the
      physical memory (RAM) and your swap memory.  Take note though, it displays
      total memory, not available and used memory.
    </para>
    
    <para>
      <inlinegraphic fileref="fig/full-2.png"></inlinegraphic>
      <guilabel>Available Swap Areas</guilabel>
      Here you will find each swap file's attributes. It shows if its
      enabled or not, the device name it has, the priority, and the size of
      the swap.
    </para>
    
    <para>
      <inlinegraphic fileref="fig/full-3.png"></inlinegraphic>
      <guilabel>Actions</guilabel>
      This is where you can get access to help, increase or decrease your
      option choice, apply your changes to the system, or close the window.
    </para>
  </sect1>
  
  <sect1 id="using-swap-man">
    <title>Using the Swap Manager</title>
    <para>
      The Swap Manager lets you do basic, administrative tasks on your swap
      partitions.  It lets you add swap files, remove swap files, and edit
      properties of swap files.
    </para>

    <sect2 id="using-swap-add">
      <title>Adding Swap</title>
      <para>
	Swap can easily be added by clicking on the <guibutton>Add</guibutton>
	button.
	A window then appears letting you configure the specifics on your
	partition.  In the <guilabel>Path</guilabel> box, put the name and the
	directory of the swap file you want to create.
      </para>

      <example>
	<title>Swap File Path</title>
	<para>
	  /swapfile1
	</para>
      </example>

      <para>
	In the size, select the size of your partition in megabytes.  It is
	recommended that you use powers of 2 (4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, etc.).
      </para>
      <para>
	The priority is...
      </para>
      <para>
	Click <guibutton>OK</guibutton> and the window will disappear. You
	new swap file will be added to the list of swap partitions and files.
	Press <guibutton>Apply</guibutton> to finalize your changes.
      </para>
    </sect2>

    <sect2 id="using-swap-delete">
      <title>Deleting Swap</title>
      <para>
	In the main window, select your partition which you want to delete.
	Pressing <guibutton>Remove</guibutton> will remove your swap after a
	confimation.  Pressing <guibutton>Apply</guibutton> will complete the
	removal of the swap.
      </para>
    </sect2>

    <sect2 id="using-swap-settings">
      <title>Editing Swap Configuration</title>
      <para>
	Your current swap files can be edited using 
	<guibutton>Settings</guibutton>.  Clicking
	<guibutton>Settings</guibutton> will open up the configuration for the
	swap partition which is selected.  This lets you configure the
	size and the priority of the partition.  Clicking on the arrows will
	change these options.  By clicking on the checkbox labeled <guilabel>Enabled</guilabel>
	, you can enable or disable the swap partition.  Clicking
	<guibutton>OK</guibutton> and <guibutton>Apply</guibutton> will make the
	changes for you.
      </para>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>
